---
description: Prefer && for optional JSX; never condition ? jsx : null
globs: **/*.tsx
alwaysApply: false
---

# JSX conditional rendering

When rendering optional UI (show this or nothing), use `&&`. Do **not** use a ternary that ends in `null` or `undefined`.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
{isMine ? (
  <Link href={actionHref}>
    <Button variant="primary">{actionLabel}</Button>
  </Link>
) : null}

{notes ? <p>{notes}</p> : null}

// ✅ GOOD
{isMine && (
  <Link href={actionHref}>
    <Button variant="primary">{actionLabel}</Button>
  </Link>
)}

{notes && <p>{notes}</p>}
```

## When a ternary is OK

Use `? :` only when choosing **between two real UI branches** (both sides render elements):

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD — both branches are UI
{isLoading ? <Spinner /> : <Content />}
```

## Guard against `0` / `''` pitfalls

Do not write `{count && <Badge />}` when `count` can be `0` (React renders `0`). Prefer an explicit boolean:

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD
{count > 0 && <Badge count={count} />}
{items.length > 0 && <List items={items} />}
{Boolean(label) && <span>{label}</span>}
```

## Self-check

- [ ] No `? (…jsx…) : null` or `? (…jsx…) : undefined`
- [ ] Optional blocks use `condition && (…)`
- [ ] Numeric/string conditions are explicit booleans when `0` / `''` would be wrong to render
